window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>1>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : RATIO, PROPORTIONS AND RATES","question":"The time (t) taken to buy fuel at a filling station varies directly directly as the number of vehicles (V) in a queue and varies inversely as the number of pumps (P), available at the station. In a station with 5 pumps, it took 10 minutes to fuel 20 vehicles.  Find the:    Relationship between t, P and V;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"t &#8733; VP &#8594; t = kVP  k = PtV  In this case, t = 10, V = 20, P = 5    k = 5 &#215; 1020 = 2.5  Therefore, the relationship is:    t= 2.5VP","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>1>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : RATIO, PROPORTIONS AND RATES","question":"The time (t) taken to buy fuel at a filling station varies directly directly as the number of vehicles (V) in a queue and varies inversely as the number of pumps (P), available at the station. In a station with 5 pumps, it took 10 minutes to fuel 20 vehicles.  Find the:  Time it takes to fuel 50 vehicles at a station with 2 pumps;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Using the relationship:  t = 2.5VP  V = 50, P = 2    t = 2.5 &#215; 502 = 62.5 minutes","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>1>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : RATIO, PROPORTIONS AND RATES","question":"The time (t) taken to buy fuel at a filling station varies directly directly as the number of vehicles (V) in a queue and varies inversely as the number of pumps (P), available at the station. In a station with 5 pumps, it took 10 minutes to fuel 20 vehicles.  Find the:  Number of pumps required to fuel 40 vehicles in 20 minutes","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Using the relationship:    t = 2.5VP  P = 2.5VPt  P = 2.5 &#215; 4020 = 5 pumps","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>2","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : RATIO, PROPORTIONS AND RATES","question":"A car travelled a distance of (2x + 13) km at 67.5 km/h and (5x - 20) km at 72 km/h. If the total time for the entire journey was 90 minutes, find the value of x.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Speed=Distance CoveredTime Taken  \u21d2Time=Distance CoveredSpeed  Totaltime=90minutes=9060hrs=32hrs  \u21d2t1+t2=32  t1=2x + 1367.5hr  t2=5x - 2072hr  \u21d22x + 1367.5+5x - 2072=32  \u21d272(2x + 13) + 67.5(5x - 20)4860=32  \u21d2144x + 936 + 337.5x - 13504860=32  \u21d2481.5x - 4144860=32  \u21d22(481.5x - 414)=3(4860)  \u21d2963x-828=14580  \u21d2963x=14580+828  \u21d2963x=15408  \u2234x=15408963=16","marks":"8","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>3","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"3","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : AREAS~~MENSURATION : LENGTHS AND PERIMETERS","question":"A circular floor of a building is to be tiled with ceramic tiles each of side 40 cm &#215; 40 cm. If the perimeter of the floor is 66 m, calculate, correct to the nearest whole number, the number of tiles required to completely tile the floor.    (Take &#960; =  22  7 )","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Perimeter of circular floor = 2&#960;r = 66  r = 602 &#215; 22/7 = 10.5m  Area of circular floor = &#960;r2  Area = 227 &#215; 10.52 = 346.5m2  Length of a side of the ceramic tiles = 40 cm = 0.4m    Area of one ceramic tile = 0.42 = 0.16m2    Number of ceramic tiles needed to cover area:    n = 346.50.16 = 2165.62 \u2245 2166 tiles (correct to the nearest whole number)","marks":"8","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>4>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram, ABCD is a circle centre O. The quadrilateral OBCD is a rhombus such that &#8736;ADO = &#8736;OBA = y and &#8736;BAD = t. Find:    the value of t;","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"\u2220BOD = 2\u2220BAD = 2t (angle at the centre is twice that at the circumference)    \u2220BCD = \u2220BOD = 2t (opposite angles of a rhombus are equal)    Reflex \u2220BOD = 2\u2220BCD = 2(2t) = 4t (angle at the centre is twice that at the circumference)    Also,    Reflex \u2220BOD = 360\u00b0 - \u2220BOD = 360\u00b0 - 2t (sum of angle at a point is 360\u00b0)    Equating the reflex \u2220BOD:    \u21d2 4t = 360\u00b0 - 2t    \u21d2 4t + 2t = 360\u00b0    \u21d2 6t = 360\u00b0    \u2234t=360\u00b06=60\u00b0","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>4>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram, ABCD is a circle centre O. The quadrilateral OBCD is a rhombus such that &#8736;ADO = &#8736;OBA = y and &#8736;BAD = t. Find:  the value of y;","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From \u2206BOD    |OB| = |OD| (radii)    \u2234 \u2206BOD is isosceles    \u2234 \u2220OBD = \u2220ODB = x    \u2220BOD = 2\u2220BAD = 120\u00b0 (angle at the centre is twice that at the circumference)    x + x + 120\u00b0 = 180\u00b0 (sum of angles in a triangle is 180\u00b0)    \u21d2 2x = 180\u00b0 - 120\u00b0    \u21d2 2x = 60\u00b0 ----- (i)    From \u2206BAD    \u21d2 60\u00b0 + (y + x) + (y + x) = 180\u00b0 (sum of angles in a triangle is 180\u00b0)    \u21d2 60\u00b0 + 2x + 2y = 180\u00b0    \u21d2 2x + 2y = 180\u00b0 - 60\u00b0    \u21d2 2x + 2y = 120\u00b0 ----- (ii)    Substitute (60\u00b0) for 2x in equation (ii)    \u21d2 60\u00b0 + 2y = 120\u00b0    \u21d2 2y = 120\u00b0 - 60\u00b0    \u21d2 2y = 60\u00b0    \u2234y=60\u00b02=30\u00b0","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>4>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram, ABCD is a circle centre O. The quadrilateral OBCD is a rhombus such that &#8736;ADO = &#8736;OBA = y and &#8736;BAD = t. Find:  &#8736;ADC","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"\u2220BCD = \u2220BOD = 120\u00b0 (opposite angles of a rhombus are equal)    |CB| = |CD| = |OB| = |OD| (all sides of a rhombus are equal)    \u2234 \u2206BCD is isosceles    Since, \u2220OBC = \u2220ODC (opposite angles of a rhombus are equal)    \u2234 \u2220DBC = \u2220BDC = x    \u2234 \u2220ADC = y + 2x = 30\u00b0 + 2(30\u00b0) = 90\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>5","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"5","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"A basket contains 3 gold-plated marbles, 4 diamond marbles and some silver marbles, all of the same size and shape. Two marbles were drawn from the basket at random one after the other without replacement. If the probability that the two marbles were all silver is 1/15, find the number of silver marbles.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Gold = 3, Diamond = 4, Silver = n    Total number of marbles = n + 3 + 4 = n + 7    Probability of drawing two silver marbles without replacement = 1/15    nn + 7 &#215; n - 1 n + 6 = 115  n(n - 1)(n + 7)(n + 6) = 115  15n(n - 1) = (n + 7)(n + 6)    15n2 - 15n = n2 + 13n + 42    15n2 - n2 - 13n - 15n - 42 = 0    14n2 - 28n - 42 = 0    14(n2 - 2n - 3) = 0    n2 - 2n - 3 = 0    n2 - 3n + n - 3 = 0    n(n - 3) + 1(n - 3) = 0    (n + 1)(n - 3) = 0    n = -1 or n = 3    Therefore, there are 3 silver marbles.","marks":"8","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>6>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SEQUENCE AND SERIES","question":"Given that (x + 2), (4x + 3) and (7x + 24) are consecutive terms of a Geometric Progression (G.P), find the:    value of x;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Since they are consecutive terms, the ratio between each is constant.    4x + 3x + 2 = 7x + 244x + 3  (4x +3)2 = (7x + 24)(x + 2)    16x2 + 24x + 9 = 7x2 + 38x + 48    16x2 - 7x2 + 24x - 38x + 9 - 48 = 0    9x2 - 14x - 39 = 0    Since (9 &#215; -39) = -351. So,  (-27 &#215; 13) gives -351 (factors of the quadratic equation)    9x2 - 27x + 13x - 39 = 0    9x(x - 3) + 13(x - 3) = 0    (9x + 13)(x - 3) = 0    9x = -13 or x = 3    x = -13/9 or x = 3","marks":"7","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>6>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SEQUENCE AND SERIES","question":"Given that (x + 2), (4x + 3) and (7x + 24) are consecutive terms of a Geometric Progression (G.P), find the:  common ratio","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Common ratio = Any termPrevious term  Using the 1st and 2nd terms:  r = 4x + 3x + 2  For x = -13/9  r = 4(-13/9) + 3-13/9 + 2  r = -25/95/9  r = -259 &#215; 95 = -5    For x = 3  r = 4(3) + 33 + 2  r = 155 = 3","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>7>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"Age  5  6  7  8  9  10 Frequency  2  2x - 1  y + 2  4  2  y - 1   The table shows the ages of 20 children in a household. Given that x : y = 1 : 2, find the:    values of x and y","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The total number of children = 20    x : y = 1 : 2     \u21d2xy=12  \u21d2 y = 2x    Summing the frequencies:    2 + 2x - 1 + y + 2 + 4 + 2 + y - 1 = 20    8 + 2x + 2y = 20    But y = 2x    2x + 2(2x) = 20 - 8 = 12    6x = 12    x = 2    y = 2(2) = 4    \u2234 x = 2 and y = 4","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>7>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"Age  5  6  7  8  9  10 Frequency  2  2x - 1  y + 2  4  2  y - 1   The table shows the ages of 20 children in a household. Given that x : y = 1 : 2, find the:  b. mean age of the children","images":[],"marking_scheme":"New table is:  Age  5  6  7  8  9  10 Frequency  2  3  6  4  2  3   Mean = &#8721;fx&#8721;f  Age(x)  Frequency  fx5  2  106  3  187  6  428  4  329  2  1810  3  30\u2211f = 20\u2211fx = 150  Mean = &#8721;fx&#8721;f = 15020  Mean = 7.5 years.","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>8>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : ANGLES OF ELEVATION AND DEPRESSION","question":"Two observers Abu and Badu, 46 m apart, observe a bird on a vertical pole from the same side of the bird. The angles of elevation of the bird from Abu's and Badu's eye are 40&#176; and 48&#176; respectively. If at the foot of the pole, Abu and Badu are on the same horizontal:    Illustrate the information in a diagram","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>8>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : ANGLES OF ELEVATION AND DEPRESSION","question":"Two observers Abu and Badu, 46 m apart, observe a bird on a vertical pole from the same side of the bird. The angles of elevation of the bird from Abu's and Badu's eye are 40&#176; and 48&#176; respectively. If at the foot of the pole, Abu and Badu are on the same horizontal:  b. Calculate, correct to one decimal place, the height of the pole.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Let the distance between Badu and the pole be x    Distance between Abu and the pole = 46 + x, angle of elevation = 40&#176;    From Abu:    tan 40&#176; = h46 + x  h = tan 40&#176;(46 + x)    From Badu:    tan 48&#176; = hx  h = x tan 48&#176;    Equating them, we have:    tan 40&#176;(46 + x) = x tan 48&#176;    0.8391(46 + x) = 1.1106x    38.5986 + 0.8391x = 1.1106x    1.1106x - 0.8391x = 38.5986    0.2715x = 38.9586    x = 38.59860.2715 = 142.17 m  h = 1.1106x = 1.1106 &#215; 142.17    \u2234 h = 157.9 m (to 1 d.p)","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>9>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"The diameter of a circle centre O is 26 cm. If a chord  PQ  is drawn such that it is 5 cm from O to the centre of the chord, calculate to the nearest whole number, the:    &#8736;POQ:","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From \u2206POR    cos\u03b1=adjhyp=513  \u03b1=cos-1(513)  \u03b1 = 67.38\u00b0    \u2234 \u2220POQ = \u03b8 = 2\u03b1 = 2(67.38\u00b0) = 135\u00b0 (to the nearest whole number)","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>9>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"The diameter of a circle centre O is 26 cm. If a chord  PQ  is drawn such that it is 5 cm from O to the centre of the chord, calculate to the nearest whole number, the:  area of the minor segment formed by the chord  PQ     [Take &#960; = 22/7]","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Area of the minor segment = Area of minor sector POQ - Area of triangle POQ    AreaofminorsectorPOQ=\u03b8360\u00d7\u03c0r2=135360\u00d7227\u00d7132=199.18cm2  PR = &radic;132 - 52&nbsp; = 12 cm    PQ = 2PR = 2(12) = 24 cm    AreaoftrianglePOR=12\u00d7bh=12\u00d724\u00d75=60cm2  \u2234 area of the minor segment formed by the chord  PQ  = 199.18 cm2 - 60 cm2 = 139 cm2 (to the nearest whole number)","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>10>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : RATIO, PROPORTIONS AND RATES","question":"In a man's will, he gave 2/5 of the total acres of his cocoa farm to the wife and 1/3 of what is left to the family. The rest of the farm was to be shared amongst his three children in the ratio 3 : 5 : 2. Given that, the child who had the least share received 8 acres, calculate the:    total acres the man left","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let the total number of acres of his land be x    2x5wenttohiswife  Remainderofthefarm=1-2x5=3x5  What goes to the family = 13 of 3x5 = x5  Total of what has been given out =2x5+x5=2x +  x 5 = 3x5  Remainderthatgoestohischildren=1-3x5=2x5  The remainder is shared in the ratio 3 : 5 : 2    Total parts of the ratio = 3 + 5 + 2 = 10    Childthatreceivedtheleastgot:210of2x5  \u21d2210&#215;2x5 = 8  \u21d22x25 = 8  \u21d2x = 25 &#215; 8  2  \u2234 x = 100 acres","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>10>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : RATIO, PROPORTIONS AND RATES","question":"In a man's will, he gave 2/5 of the total acres of his cocoa farm to the wife and 1/3 of what is left to the family. The rest of the farm was to be shared amongst his three children in the ratio 3 : 5 : 2. Given that, the child who had the least share received 8 acres, calculate the:  ii. Number of acres the wife received.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"2x5wenttohiswife  \u2234Number of acres the wife received = 2 &#215; 1005 = 40 acres","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>10>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SIMPLE INTEREST AND COMPOUND INTEREST","question":"The list price of a Television set is $ 1,600.00. It can be purchased by a deposit of $ 400.00 and the rest of the amount paid by 12 monthly installment at 25 % per annum simple interest. If the Television set is purchased by installment, find the total cost.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"List price = $ 1,600.00    Deposit = $ 400.00    Annual interest rate = 25 %    Time = 12 months    Principal = $ 1,600.00 - $ 400.00 = $ 1,200.00 (since interest is paid only on the face value)    Monthlyinterestrate=25%12  I=PTR100  I=1200 \u00d7 12 \u00d7 25/12100=$300.00  Amount = P + I = $ 1,200.00 + $ 300.00 = $ 1,500.00    \u2234 total cost = $ 1,500.00 + $ 400.00 = $ 1,900.00","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>11>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"COORDINATE GEOMETRY OF STRAIGHT LINES : CONCEPT OF THE X-Y PLANE AND COORDINATES OF POINTS ON THE X-Y PLANE","question":"Find the equation of the line that passes through the origin and the point of intersection of the lines x + 2y = 7, and x - y = 4","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"To find the point of intersection, solve the simultaneous equation formed by the two lines    x + 2y = 7 ----- (i)    x - y = 4 ----- (ii)    Subtract equation (ii) from (i):    \u21d2 3y = 3    \u21d2 y = 1    From equation (ii)    x = 4 + y    \u21d2 x = 4 + 1 = 5    Point of intersection = (5, 1)    The equation of the line that passes through the origin and the point above:    Slope of line = y2 - y1x2 - x1 = 1 - 05 - 0=15  Using y - y1 = m(x - x1):    \u21d2y-1=15(x-5)  \u21d2y-1=15x-1  \u2234y=15xory=0.2xor5y=xorx-5y=0","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>11>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : TRIANGLES AND POLYGONS","question":"The ratio of an interior angle to an exterior angle of a regular polygon 4 : 1, find the:    number of sides","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Size of an interior angle = (n - 2)180n  Size of an exterior angle = 360n  Ratio of an interior angle to an exterior angle = 4 : 1  i.e.IE=41  I = 4E    This means the size of an interior angle is 4 times the size of an exterior angle.    (n - 2)180n = 4 &#215; 360n  Since denominators are equal, we equate numerators    n - 2(180) = 4 &#215; 360    Dividing both sides by 180:    n - 2 = 4 &#215; 2 = 8    \u2234 n = 8 + 2 = 10 sides","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>11>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : TRIANGLES AND POLYGONS","question":"The ratio of an interior angle to an exterior angle of a regular polygon 4 : 1, find the:  value of the exterior angle","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Value of an exterior angle = 360n = 36010 = 36&#176;","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>11>b>iii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : TRIANGLES AND POLYGONS","question":"The ratio of an interior angle to an exterior angle of a regular polygon 4 : 1, find the:  sum of the interior angles of the polygon","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Sum of the interior angles of the polygon = (n - 2)180    = (10 - 2) &#215; 180    = 8 &#215; 180     = 1440&#176;","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>12>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram  PR  is a tangent to the circle O at Q. &#8736;POQ = 56o and  PO  intersects  SQ  at V such that &#8736;SVP = 109o. Calculate:    &#8736;TQP;","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"&#8736;QST = 12&#215;56=28&#176;(angle at circumference is half angle at centre)  \u2220TQP = \u2220QST = 28&#176; (angle between tangent and chord equals angle in alternate segment)","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>12>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram  PR  is a tangent to the circle O at Q. &#8736;POQ = 56o and  PO  intersects  SQ  at V such that &#8736;SVP = 109o. Calculate:  &#8736;QTS","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From \u2206TOQ    |TO| = |OQ| (radii)    \u2234 \u2206TOQ is an isosceles    \u2220OTQ = \u2220OQT = x    \u21d2 x + x + \u2220POQ = 180\u00b0 (sum of angles in a triangle is 180\u00b0)    \u21d2 2x + 56\u00b0 = 180\u00b0    \u21d2 2x = 180\u00b0 - 56\u00b0    \u21d2 2x = 124\u00b0    \u21d2 x = 62\u00b0    \u2234 \u2220OTQ = 62\u00b0    From \u2206STV    \u2220VTS + \u2220SVP + \u2220QST = 180\u00b0 (sum of angles in a triangle is 180\u00b0)    \u21d2 \u2220VTS  + 109\u00b0 + 28\u00b0 = 180\u00b0    \u21d2 \u2220VTS  + 137\u00b0 = 180\u00b0    \u21d2 \u2220VTS = 180\u00b0 - 137\u00b0    \u21d2 \u2220VTS = 43\u00b0    \u2220QTS = \u2220OTQ + \u2220VTS    \u2220QTS = 62\u00b0 + 43\u00b0    \u2234 \u2220QTS = 105\u00b0","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>12>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : EXPANSION AND FACTORISATION","question":"Simplify:  2n2 - 3n - 2  2n2 + 3n + 1  &#215;  n2 - 1  n2 - 4  .","images":[],"marking_scheme":"2n2 - 3n - 2  2n2 + 3n + 1  &#215;  n2 - 1  n2 - 4  .  =  (2n + 1)(n - 2) (2n + 1)(n + 1)  &#215;  (n + 1)(n - 1) (n + 2)(n - 2) .  = n - 1n + 2","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>13>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram ABT is a circle centre O.  PQ  is a tangent to the circle at T and ABC is a straight line. TC bisects &#8736;BTQ, &#8736;BAT = 44&#176; and &#8736;PTA = 60&#176;. Find &#8736;ACT","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"&#8736;ABT = \u2220PTA = 60\u00b0 (angle between tangent and chord equals angle in alternate segment)    &#8736;ATB = 180 - (60 + 44) = 76\u00b0 (sum of angles in a triangle is 180\u00b0)    &#8736;QTB = \u2220BAT = 44\u00b0 (angle between tangent and chord equals angle in alternate segment)    Since TC bisects &#8736;BTQ, &#8736;BTC = 22\u00b0    Therefore, &#8736;ATC = 76 + 22 = 98\u00b0    &#8736;ACT = 180 - (98 + 44) (sum of angles in a triangle is 180\u00b0)    \u2234 &#8736;ACT = 38\u00b0","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>13>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : VOLUMES","question":"The circumference of the base of a cylindrical tank is 11 m. The height of the tank is 3 m more than 6 times the base radius. Calculate the:    [Take &#960; = 22/7]    radius","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Circumference = 2&#960;r    r = Circumference2&#960;  Circumference = 11 m    r = 112 &#215; 22/7 = 74 m  \u2234 r = 1.75 m","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>13>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : VOLUMES","question":"The circumference of the base of a cylindrical tank is 11 m. The height of the tank is 3 m more than 6 times the base radius. Calculate the:    [Take &#960; = 22/7]  height;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Height of tank is 3 m more than 6 times the base radius.    h = 6r + 3 = 6(1.75) + 3    h = 10.5 + 3    \u2234 h = 13.5 m","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2024>13>b>iii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : VOLUMES","question":"The circumference of the base of a cylindrical tank is 11 m. The height of the tank is 3 m more than 6 times the base radius. Calculate the:    [Take &#960; = 22/7]  volume of the tank","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Volume of cylinder = &#960;r2h    Volume of the tank = 227 &#215; (1.75)2 &#215; 13.5  \u2234Volume of the tank = 129.94 m3","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"}];